<subSubSection id="C31B6527FFD8FFFA2D88FB5CC9E565AE" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BBE36ACFFD8FFFA2D88FB5CC9E565AE" blockId="24.[151,1436,602,1228]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B975EABEFFD8FFFA2D88FB5CCA0F65C6" bold="true" box="[198,343,1162,1188]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Etymology:</emphasis>
The trivial name 
<taxonomicName id="4C014D2FFFD8FFFA2F61FB5DC9DF65C6" authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2008" box="[559,647,1163,1188]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Opitzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicula">
<emphasis id="B975EABEFFD8FFFA2F61FB5DC9DF65C6" box="[559,647,1163,1188]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">apicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
stems from the Latin diminutive 
<emphasis id="B975EABEFFD8FFFA2955FB5DCF2665C6" box="[1051,1150,1163,1188]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">apiculus</emphasis>
, referring to the yellow coloration on the apex of the last antennomere.
</paragraph>
